"Hurkmans R., Terink W., Uijlenhoet R., Torfs P., Jacob D., Troch P.A.","Changes in streamflow dynamics in the Rhine basin under three high-resolution regional climate scenarios",2010,"Journal of Climate","23","3",,"679","699",,,10.1175/2009JCLI3066.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77950987931&partnerID=40&md5=0da1aefaccfff2f84d0ebbf7cd394a76","Hydrology and Quantitative Water Management Group, Wageningen University, Wageningen, Netherlands; Max Planck Institut für Meteorologie, Hamburg, Germany; Department of Hydrology and Water Resources, The University of Arizona, Tucson, AZ, United States","Hurkmans, R., Hydrology and Quantitative Water Management Group, Wageningen University, Wageningen, Netherlands; Terink, W., Hydrology and Quantitative Water Management Group, Wageningen University, Wageningen, Netherlands; Uijlenhoet, R., Hydrology and Quantitative Water Management Group, Wageningen University, Wageningen, Netherlands; Torfs, P., Hydrology and Quantitative Water Management Group, Wageningen University, Wageningen, Netherlands; Jacob, D., Max Planck Institut für Meteorologie, Hamburg, Germany; Troch, P.A., Department of Hydrology and Water Resources, The University of Arizona, Tucson, AZ, United States","Because of global warming, the hydrologic behavior of the Rhine basin is expected to shift from a combined snowmelt-and rainfall-driven regime to a more rainfall-dominated regime. Previous impact assessments have indicated that this leads, on average, to increasing streamflow by ~30% in winter and spring and decreasing streamflow by a similar value in summer. In this study, high-resolution (0.088°) regional climate scenarios conducted with the regional climate model REMO (REgional MOdel) for the Rhine basin are used to force a macroscale hydrological model. These climate scenarios are based on model output from the ECHAM5-Max Planck Institute Ocean Model (MPI-OM) global climate model, which is in turn forced by three Special Report on Emissions Scenarios (SRES) emission scenarios: A2, A1B, and B1. The Variable Infiltration Capacity model (VIC; version 4.0.5) is used to examine changes in streamflow at various locations throughout the Rhine basin. Average streamflow, peak flows, low flows, and several water balance terms are evaluated for both the first and second half of the twenty-first century. The results reveal a distinct contrast between those periods. The first half is dominated by increased precipitation, causing increased streamflow throughout the year. During the second half of the century, a streamflow increase in winter/spring and a decrease in summer is found, similar to previous studies. This is caused by 1) temperature and evapotranspiration, which are considerably higher during the second half of the century; 2) decreased precipitation in summer; and 3) an earlier start of the snowmelt season. Magnitudes of peak flows increase during both periods, and the magnitudes of streamflow droughts increase only during the second half of the century. © 2010 American Meteorological Society.",,"Climate scenarios; Emission scenario; Global climate model; High resolution; Hydrological models; Impact assessments; Low flow; Macro scale; Max Planck Institute; Model outputs; Ocean model; Peak flows; Regional climate; Regional climate models; Regional model; Rhine basin; Snow-melt season; Snowmelt; Special report on emissions scenarios; Variable infiltration capacity models; Water balance; Global warming; Oceanography; Rain; Snow melting systems; Stream flow; Water supply; Climate models; climate modeling; drought; evapotranspiration; global warming; peak flow; precipitation (climatology); regional climate; river basin; streamflow; water budget; Rhine Basin",,,,,,"Adger, N., Summary for policy makers (2007) Climate Change 2007: Impacts, Adaptation and Vulnerability, pp. 7-22. , M. L. Parry et al., Eds., Cambridge University Press; Akhtar, M., Ahmad, N., Booij, M.J., Use of regional climate model simulat